article.description:
Alana Beard scored 18 points and blocked a
last-second 3-point attempt by Shanna Zolman that could have tied
the game, preserving the Washington Mystics' 80-77 victory over the
San Antonio Silver Stars on Friday night.
article.headline: Mystics blow big lead, hold on against Silver Stars
article.linkText: Mystics blow big lead, hold on against Silver Stars
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Alana Beard always is going to be a scoring threat for the Washington Mystics. An instant before the buzzer sounded Friday night, she was a defensive stopper, too. Beard scored 18 points and blocked a last-second 3-point attempt by Shanna Zolman that could have tied the game, preserving the Mystics' 80-77 victory over the San Antonio Silver Stars on Friday. "Coach (Richie Adubato) is always telling me in practice that I need to get my hands up on defense," said Beard, the sixth-leading scorer in the WNBA. "Tonight just shows that he is right. I need to give the props to Coach for that block." Washington (12-11) led by as much as 14 points early in the second half before San Antonio rallied. The Mystics were up by 10 points with 4:28 remaining in the game. The Silver Stars had two chances to tie in the final 20 seconds. Sophia Young missed an off-balance shot in the lane that was rebounded by Nakia Sanford with 11 seconds left. Nikki Teasley hit the first of two free-throw attempts for the Mystics before the final shot by Zolman. San Antonio (11-12) had a chance to even its home record at .500 for the first time this season. The Silver Stars have lost four of five and fell back into a fourth-place tie with Seattle in the Western Conference, with Phoenix just a half-game back for the final playoff spot. Agnieszka Bibrzycka scored 19 points and was 5-of-7 from 3-point range for San Antonio. "I'm proud of the way we fought back," Silver Stars coach Dan Hughes said. "I would have liked to have seen us finish one more play." Chasity Melvin scored 16 for the Mystics and Teasley added 14. Washington had an 18-7 edge in offensive rebounding, which led to the Mystics' 17-3 advantage in second-chance points. Washington built a 13-point lead with 4:42 left in the first half by beating San Antonio on the offensive boards. The Mystics had an 8-0 edge in second-chance points at halftime and were up 9-3 in offensive rebounds. They also shot the ball well. When Crystal Robinson hit a 3-pointer to give Washington a 41-28 lead, it was the ninth basket for the Mystics in their first 12 shots of the second quarter. Washington was 8-of-9 during a span of 3:41, turning a two-point lead for San Antonio into the 13-point advantage for the Mystics.

Game notes
Melvin's streak of double-doubles for Washington ended at three after she was limited to six rebounds. ... Silver Stars starting center Chantelle Anderson left the game with a left knee injury less than a minute into the second half. Anderson was coming off back-to-back double-figure-scoring games for the first time this season.
